            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Well... this is embarrassing. I spoke a little too soon when I said I had it working. I'm not particularly great at C, so I'm not sure exactly what I'm missing.\n\ncurrently I've made the following 2 changes:\n\n1. added a function that is meant to append `<R:` to the start of the keybinding, and `>` to the end.\n```\nstatic void handle_key_event(TermInput *input, TermKeyKey *key)\n\n{\n  char *ptr = key->utf8;\n  char buf[64];\n  size_t len = 0;\n  buf[len++] = '<';\n  len += (size_t)snprintf(buf + len, sizeof(buf) - len, \"R:\");\n  while (*ptr) {\n    buf[len++] = *ptr;\n    assert(len < sizeof(buf));\n    ptr++;\n  }\n  buf[len++] = '>';\n  assert(len < sizeof(buf));\n  tinput_enqueue(input, buf, len);\n}\n```\n\n2. replaced the switch case that previously blocked release inputs with an if/else statement that runs the above function rather than any of the other character forwarding functions upon the detection of a release event.\n```\nif (key.event == TERMKEY_EVENT_RELEASE) {\n      handle_key_event(input, &key);\n    } else \n```\n\nI'm struggling to understand exactly what I'm getting wrong here, partly because I can't seem to find a way to easily log or print things to a terminal or... well... anywhere? I most certainly jumped directly into the deep end without a rope here.",
